otland":"Cromartyshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1299–1369":"1299–1369","1303–1373":"1303–1373","1325–1395":"1325–1395","1272–1342":"1272–1342","1276–1346":"1276–1346","1325":"1325","1369":"1369","1303":"1303","1346":"1346","1299":"1299","1342":"1342","1276":"1276","1395":"1395","1373":"1373","1272":"1272","Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Cromartyshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Urquhart","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Ross and Cromarty): habitational name from any of various places in Scotland so called, notably the barony of Urquhart (Inverness), or places in Ross and Cromarty, Morayshire, and Fife. All are thought to derive from Pictish <i>ar</i> ‘on, by’ + Pictish <i>carden</i> ‘enclosure’ or ‘wood, copse’. Some bearers of this name trace their descent from William <i>de Urchard</i>, who fought for Robert the Bruce between 1297 and 1328."],"variants":[{"name":"Orcutt","meanings":["English (Staffordshire): perhaps a much altered form of Scottish   Urquhart  ."]},{"name":"Orchard","meanings":["topographic or occupational name from residence near (or perhaps employment at) an orchard, Middle English <i>orchard</i> (Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i>).","habitational name from any of the places called Orchard. Those in Devon and Somerset are named from Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i> (a compound of <i>wort</i>, <i>wyrt</i> ‘plant’ (later associated with Latin <i>hortus</i> ‘garden’) + <i>geard</i> ‘yard, enclosure’), while East and West Orchard near Shaftesbury in Dorset derive from Primitive Welsh <i>ar</i> ‘beside, in front of, facing’ + <i>ced</i> ‘wood’.","rare variant of Scottish   Urquhart  . Compare   Orahood  ."]}]},{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Francis Urquhart was born in 1299, in Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland, his father, David Urquhart, was 27 and his mother, Eleanore Seton, was 23. He had at least 1 son with Baroness Rosalind de Haye. He died in 1369, in Scotland, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1299–1369":"1299–1369","1303–1373":"1303–1373","1325–1395":"1325–1395","1272–1342":"1272–1342","1276–1346":"1276–1346","1325":"1325","1369":"1369","1303":"1303","1346":"1346","1299":"1299","1342":"1342","1276":"1276","1395":"1395","1373":"1373","1272":"1272","Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Cromartyshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Cromarty, Cromartyshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1299–1369":"1299–1369","1303–1373":"1303–1373","1325–1395":"1325–1395","1272–1342":"1272–1342","1276–1346":"1276–1346","1325":"1325","1369":"1369","1303":"1303","1346":"1346","1299":"1299","1342":"1342","1276":"1276","1395":"1395","1373":"1373","